column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While travelling on FM3131 and Highway 172 in Ganado, Texas the tractor-tanker unit was involved in a vehicle accident.  The tractor-tanker unit overturned and end up in a roadside ditch.  The accident caused a small puncture in the center of the tanker as well as a leak of approximately one quart of diesel fuel.  The Texas Highway Patrol, Jackson County Hazmat Team, Ganado Fire Department and Praxair, Inc.-NAIG Liquid Bulk Distribution Emergency Response Team responded to assess the site.  Ganado Fire Department personnel performed the cleanup of the diesel fuel using absorbent pads.  The tanker was uprighted and the Praxair, Inc.-NAIG Liquid Bulk Distribution Emergency Response Team vented the remaining product inside of the tanker.  No injuries or exposures were reported as a result of the hazardous material.
column169: Since the release was accidental and may have been related to a vehicle accident, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Praxair, Inc.-NAIG Liquid Bulk Distribution will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: While conducting a daily inspection at the Veolia, Port Washington, WI terminal, it was discovered that an electrical bushing that was in temporary storage was leaking. Based on further inspection of the bushings it appeared that a fluid level guage was leaking. The material leaking from the bushing was PCB contaminated (83 ppm) mineral oil. The spilled material covered an area within the concrete containment area of 1.5 feet by 12 feet. Assuming the liquid was less than an 0.125 inches thick, the volume of liquid spilled was ~1.5 gallons. Based on the concentration of PCB this amounted to 0.000988 lb. of PCB, well below the RQ for PCB. Following discovery, the spill was reported to the shift supervisor and clean up operations were started immediately. The spill was cleaned up using the double wash double rinse procedure defined in 40 CFR 761. Clean up debris was added to the manifest for shipment to a permitted facility for disposal.
column169: The transport and disposal of electrical equipment such as transformers and bushings present a number of challenges. Most of this equipment will not fit into a package for transport. As such, we will continue to place an emphasis on inspection and load securement when the equipment is originally picked up from the offeror.

column168: Gasoline was loaded onto the transport at the Marathon Petroleum Refinery in Robinson, IL and then ethanol was to be added at Superior Oil in Robinson, IL. While the ethanol was being added the overfill prevention failed and product was forced out the dome lid and onto the ground. The pump did not stop and the driver tried to diconnect the loading coupler to stop the flow of product. This is when the driver was contaminated with product. Approximately 100 gallons was released which was contained inside the facility. The fire department and EMC responded. The fire deparment foamed the area to prevent ignition during cleanup. The driver was taken to the hospital, treated, and released. Treated for exposure to ethanol. The terminal personell conducted the cleanup.
column169: The incident is still under investigation. If the Scully probe is bad in the trialer it will be repaired immediately. If the Scully at teh terminal is bad, Superior Oil will be responsible for the repairs. Marathon has not been loading at this facility and will not until the investigation is complete and repairs are made.

column169: We are working on getting all our hoses tested.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. While preparing to unload a tear in a super sack was discovered. Fee Corp personnel removed the affected package from the trailer. The affected package was emptied into four(4) 55-gallon drums. The cleanup supplies and free product were swept and placed into one(1) 55-gallon drum. Cytec Industries will coordinate disposal of the spent material. The Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. driver and Cytec Industries personnel sought treament for exposure. No adverse effects were reported. The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling proceedures to all personnel.

column168: Driver had finished transferring product from the cargo tank to a customer storage tank using a pump. column168: During the unloading of a trailer we noticed an odor coming from inside the trailer. We discovered a piece of steel had pushed up against a tote. When we moved the steel the tote began to leak. We got the tote lowered over a recovery drum to catch the leak. This lasted about 20 Minutes collected approximately 8 gallons. The tote sealed itself and quit leaking. We drained the remaining material into a new tote supplied by the consignee. We shipped the new tote and the damaged tote to the consignee. The recovery drum with the 8 gallons is scheduled to be removed by a environmental recovery company for disposal.
column169: Better loading techniques training at all breakbulk terminals. Also implementation of procedures to insure that all hazardous material totes are loaded away from sharp objects that could pierce the container.

column168: UTLX 58636, residue, last contained Ethanol, was set to a shop track for safety appliance repairs. A CSXT carmen smelled an odor when the car was moved into the shop area. The carmen notified his supervisor and the car was moved out of the shop and the CSXT PSCC was notified. The HazMat Call Duty Officer call a HazMat Sentinel, Paul Watson Jr. to investigate the report. The HazMat Sentinel found that the manway was releasing vapors, from bolts 3 & 4 area of an 8 bolt manway. The HazMat Call Duty Officer called Miller Environmental Group to respond and handle the incident with the HazMat Sentinel. Miller Environmental reported that upon opening the manway the gasket was abraded and the manway nozzle was corroded with rust and scale. Miller Environmental personnel cleaned off the rust and scale, applied a layer of Teflon gasket material and re-do ed the manway tightening the bolts in proper sequence. UTLX 58636 was staged for 30 minutes and the manway was checked with a CGI, no vapor leaks were found. The tank car was released for repairs and then disposition. Transflo — Savage Operations, Boston/Aliston, MA. was notified of the manway repairs and was it requested that a nozzle gasket be installed prior to loading any product into UTLX 58636.  Cause Code: 209  NARRI: 2(4±3+O)x(2+0) 28

column168: APPARENTLY WHILE BEING LOADED AT ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER DRUM WAS STRUCK DURING THE LOADING PROCESS CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK THROUGH GOUGE HOLE.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS WERE SPILLED IN TRAILER.
column169: FOLLOW-UP WITH ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER AND ASSOCIATE ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: FILE-06-172 DOT & OMC         SHIPPER-DELICIOUS BRANDS        AWB#-DFW 8950530035 EW     ON 12/19/2006 AT 0850 EST, A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "D" BUILDING OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING AN ODOR. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, IHEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOXES CONTAINING 6 X 8 OZ GLASS BOTTLES OF DIFFUSER OIL. THE INNER BOXES WERE MARKED CONSUMER COMMODITY, ORM-D, BUT THE OUTER PACKAGING HAD NO MARKINGS/LABELS TO SIGNIFY HAZ. DUE TO 4 OF THE GLASS BOTTLES BEING BROKEN, A TOTAL OF 32 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS   SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA TRUCK #4249.     THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.   CLEAR OF SCENE: 1005.   THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: Driver was making delivery of shipment when leak was discovered. 2 of 17 totes were unloaded and trailer floor found wet from released material.  Trailer door was closed immediately and outside response was called and received by Hepaco.  a valve on 1 tote was found to be in the open position, therefore allowing the contained material to leak onto trailer floor.  Released material formed into a gel like substance once exposed to air.  The open valve was closed and each tote cleaned up and offered for delivery.  Spilled material was cleaned up by Hepaco and prepared for proper disposal.  Clean up of ccontaminated trailer was conducted after being returned to terminal facility by Hepaco.
column169: Contact was made with shipper of the product with concern about positioning of valves on totes and what could have possibly caused the valve to get into the 'Open' position.  Future shipments will be better inspected to make sure that vales are in their proper 'Closed' position before transporting to destination.

column168: A BNSF SWITCHMAN REPORTED GATX 61986 LOCATED IN THE RAILYARD BOWL TRACKS EMANATING PRODUCT ODOR.  BNSF OPERATING PERSONNEL SUSPENDED ALL HUMPING ACTIVITIES AND CORDONED OFF THE AREA NEAR GATX 61986.  BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDERS INSPECTED GATX 61986 FINDING THE 280.5 PSI PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) EMANATING PRODUCT ODOR.  RESPONDERS WITH A NEW 0-RING KIT REPLACED THE STEM AND SEAT O-RINGS ALONG WITH THE O-RING KEEPER OR RETAINER WHICH ELIMINATED ANY FURTHER ESCAPING VAPORS.  THE STEM O-RING REMOVED APPEARED PINCHED AND FLATTENED ON ONE SIDE.  ALSO, THE RESPONDERS FOUND THE SAMPLE LINE CLOSURE PLUG LOOSE WITH THIS VALVE CLOSED.  RESPONDERS REMOVED THE LOOSE PLUG, APPLIED NEW TEFLON TAPE TO THE THREADS AND SECURED THE PLUG.  RESPONSE WAS CONCLUDED PRIOR TO 2255 HRS. PST, 12/01/06 AND YARD OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  BNSF YARD OPERATING PERSONNEL REPORTED THAT 150 RAILCARS OF LOST HUMPING PRODUCTIVITY WERE INCURRED DURING THIS EVENT.

column168: The dockworker began unloading the trailer. As he was pulling pallets out of the trailer and went back to get another, he noticed that the next pallet had HMs on it. As he checked the pallet out before picking it up, he noticed that the HM label on one of the cartons at the bottom of the pallet was very faded. When he checked it out, he found that the carton had a hole in it, looked like a puncture from a forklift blade, and the carton was slightly wet. He notified the supervisor. They carefully removed it from the pallet and opened it up. The top of the can was crushed and the lid popped off. About 1/2 of the gallon can was missing, however there was no liquid on the floor of the trailer. There were no signs of a spill, except that the carton was slightly wet.We put the can in a recovery drum and held it in STK OS&D for disposition.
column169: It is our suggestion that pallets or plywood be placed in between HMs when loading them on a trailer. This would help protect the HMs on the pallet when the next pallet is loaded into the trailer. Should the forklift driver have the forks to high, or the blades extend beyond the pallet he would hit the pallet or plywood and stop , before causing any damage to the HMs.      We held a dock meeting to review the incident and praised the dock worker for his appropriate actions. He noticed the pallet had hms on it and before picking it up he checked the pallet out. He wanted to make sure that the pallet was intact, and that nothing would fall off the back when he picked it up. When he noticed the faded label and found that it was wet, he went and notified the supervisor. Although it is difficult to determine where the incident occurred, the crew agreed that the best way to prevent this would be to surround all HMs shipments with pallets or plywood.

A LPG truck was venting the liquid hose as a safety precausion step prior to disconnecting the hose from the truck.  When the loader was venting he noticed the hose was not depressuring.  Venting the hose typically takes 15 - 20 seconds. LPG product was going to the atmosphere for this period of time.     The event was mitigated by closing an upstream valve to isolate the system.    Liquid hose was then vented and disconnected.
column169: Trained all truck drivers on the procedures at our loading rack to ensure compliance.  Discussed with truck drivers the max time that is should take to vent a hose.  In the event the hose is not depressured in that time frame, The operations department should then be contacted to troubleshoot the problem.    Replaced leaking valve to ensure isolation.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD DIFFICULTY OBTAINING PROPER CAMLOCK FITTING.  DRIVER USED OLD METAL SEALS AS SHIMS TO OBTAIN A TIGHT FITTING.  THE DRIVER THEN OPENED THE INTERNAL HYDRAULIC VALVE, THEN PARTIALLY OPENED THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  THE CAMLOCK FITTING ON THE HOSE STARTED TO LEAK ALMOST INSTANTLY SPRAYING PRODUCT UPWARD STRIKING THE DRIVER UNDER HIS FACE SHIELD ON HIS FACE AND NECK.  THE DRIVER WAS WEARING ALL PRESCRIBED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE).  BY REACTION TO THE SPRAY THE DRIVER CLOSED EXTERNAL AND INTERNAL VALVES AT THE SAME TIME.
column169: 1.  DRIVERS WILL FIND SAFETY SHOWER AND TEST TO ENSURE THAT IT WORKS PROPERLY BEFORE       BEGINNING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.    2.  ALL DRIVERS WILL BE RETRAINED TO ENSURE THEY HAVE A COMPLETE UNDERSTANDING AND       CAPABLE OF FOLLOWING ALL SOP PROCEDURES.    3. column168: Driver was picking up a relayed cargo tank at the tankwash.  During the pretrip inspection he noticed a drip coming from the external valve on compartment #1. column168: ENGC-12685 was loaded in XMP (Minneapolis, MN) and this shipment was placed on the left side of the trailer approximatley 18 feet from the rear on the floor. All of the spilled product had evaporated by the time it had arrived in Spokane. Upon discovery in Spokane, the trailer was abandoned until our safety department was contacted along with the shipper emergency contact. A Conway Safety Manager was contacted first and he advised that I needed to call the emergency number listed on the BOL. Chemtrec took the report information and it is filed under report number 12202006064. He called the shipper contact which in turn called me to access the situation. MARCOR advised that we could clean the spilled product as long as we wore rubber gloves. I donned the gloves and found 1- 1 gallon jug to be empty. I removed the other jugs in the carton and recoupled them into clean boxes, properly labelled them and sent them to destination.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL
column168: The incident at issue involved the receipt of an undeclared shipment of a radioactive material by GE Healthcare (GEHC) at its GoldSeal facility in Waukesha WI. This shipment unexpectedly occurred in connection with a return by Cardiosonix Laboratories (“Cardiosonix”) of separate, leased GE imaging equipment. The material at issue consisted of two Cs-137 solid sources registered to Cardiosonix. The sources were secured in a shielded container at all relevant times and there was no release.     Cardiosonix had leased a GE Functional(“Imaging System”), which contains no radioactive materials, from GE Healthcare Financial Services   (HFS). Cardiosonix subsequently defaulted on its lease. Cardiosonix or its agents thereafter packed the components of the Imaging System into several boxes, deposited them at a Public Storage facility in Hialeah, FL. and advised HFS of their whereabouts in October 2006.     HFS then contacted GEHC to arrange for transportation, and GEHC hired United Van Lines to transport the closed boxes from the Florida storage facility to GEHC’s GoldSeal’s facility in Waukesha, WI. HFS subsequently sold the returned equipment to GEHC.     On December 12, 2006 at approximately 12:00 pm, the Cardiosonix shipping boxes arrived on the dock of GE GoldSeal Global Services Facility. During the receiving and inspection process, GE technicians found within one of the boxes, amidst other equipment (cables, etc.), a closed lead container with a Radioactive Materials label on it. Upon discovery, the technicians immediately obtained a survey meter and checked for radiation levels from the box containing the material. It was determined that the materials were Cs- 137 sealed sources with readings measuring approximately 7 microrem above background.     Site Radiation Safety Officer was contacted for further inspection. Site RSO placed the container to a shielded area for inspection. Leak tests were performed on the lead box, the container for the poly bottle, the poly bottle and the rod source of Cs-l37. Results showed that the sources were intact. GEHC EHS was immediately notified. GEHC EHS review confirmed that the material is not exempt from transportation regulations.     GEHC had no reason to believe that these Cs-137 sources were being shipped as part of the Cardiosonix equipment return, as the Imaging System at issue does not contain any radioactive sources. Thus, no sources should have been included by Cardiosonix in its equipment return.     As part of the investigation GEHC made numerous attempts to contact Cardiosonix, who remains the owner of record of the sources at issue. Cardiosonix could not be reached. GEHC subsequently returned the Cardiosonix sealed sources to the manufacturer in accordance with all applicable DOT/NRC requirements.
column169: GE to further review its equipment return process to analyze what additional measures it could implement to minimize the chance of similar incidents occurring in the future.

column168: A BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED TILX 190001 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AREA OF THIS TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS IN THE RAILYARD. RESPONDER’S DETAILED INSPECTION FOUND THE LIQUID VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN AND THE CORRESPONDING CLOSURE PLUG ONLY HAND TIGHT. THE RESPONDER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE OPEN VALVE WHICH ENDED FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE BY APPROXIMATELY 2145 HRS. CST, 12/10/06. AFTERWARDS, THE RESPONDER REMOVED THE CLOSURE PLUG AND BRUSHED OFF THE OLD DETERIORATED TEFLON TAPE AROUND THE PLUG THREADS. NEW TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED AROUND THE THREADS OF THE PLUG. THE PLUG WAS REAPPLIED AND PROPERLY TOOL TIGHTENED. ALL PRODUCT SPILLAGE EVAPORATED.

column168: ON THE EVENING OF DECEMBER 13, 2006 AT APPROXIMATELY 8PM, AND IRVING OIL TERMINALS, INC. (IOTI) TRANSPORT VEHICLE CARRYING GASOLINE WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON ROUTE 1 IN BELFAST, MAINE. THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS LOADED EARLIER THAT EVENING AT LOTIS SEARSPORT, ME MARINE TERMINAL.     WHILE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND IN THE VICINITY OF THE BELFAST BAY BREWING COMPANY, THE IOTI DRIVER NOTICED TWO VEHICLES APPROACHING THE TRANSPORT — ONE IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE, AND ANOTHER IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANE HEADING NORTH — THE VEHICLES APPEARED TO BE RACING.     TO AVOID HITTING THE VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTH IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANE, THE IOTI DRIVER PULLED INTO THE SOUTHBOUND BREAKDOWN LANE. WHILE PULLING OVER, THE WHEELS OF THE TRANSPORT WERE CAUGHT IN THE SOFT SHOULDER, PULLING THE TRANSPORT OFF OF THE ROAD AND INTO THE PARKING AREA OF THE BEL CAST BAY BREWING COMPANY. THE TRANSPORT ROLLED OVER AND SETTLED ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE VEHICLE.     THE ROLLOVER DAMAGED COMPARTMENT #1 (COMPARTMENT DIRECTLY BEHIND CAB OF TRUCK) OF THE TRANSPORT RESULTING IN A 3 INCH CRACK TO THE BOTTOM/MIDDLE PORTION OF THE COMPARTMENT. GASOLINE SLOWLY LEAKED FROM COMPARTMENT #1 FOR 5 HOURS RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 1,500 GALLONS.
column169: DRIVER LEFT ROAD TO AVOID ONCOMING TRAFFIC. INCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.

column168: Root cause of spill was that the driver over filled the tank by mis calculating the amount of gallons in the tank before the start of the delivery.  The station was closed at the time of the delivery.  There are alarms on the station and they were working at the time of the spill.  The problem with the high limit alarms are that they only sound inside of the station and cannot be heard outside where the driver was making the delivery. The 10% safe fill devices in the fills were not working at all at the time of the spill.    Two sewers were affected and Milro Associates were called in for the clean up of the incident.
column169: The high limit alarms should be heard outside of the building if the station is going to take deliveries when the station is closed.  Also the 10% fill devices in the fill should be checked and repaired before the next delivery.

Driver was talking on the phone to supervisor and overfilled trailer while loading - approx. 36 gallons of crude oil were released through trailer vent line. Per supervisor, site was cleaned up and expected clean up costs are $900.00 - A vaccum truck and bobtail backhoe were used.
column169: Spill was attributed to driver inattention. Drivers were instructed NO to use the phone while loading or unloading unless its an emergency situation.

column168: Driver was making a propane delivery on private property.  The tank he was filling began to leak during the offloading process due to a pinhole in the bottom of the tank.  The propane released without incident and dissapated in the air.
column169: Remedial training was provided to the driver.

column168: IMPROPER LOADING OF SHIPMENT CAUSED THE SKID TO FALL OVER.  ONE PAIL CRACKED OPEN WHEN IT HIT THE FLOOR RELEASING 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT.
column169: LOI AND RETRAINING ISSUED TO LOADING DSR AND RESPONSIBLE FOS WILL RECEIVE APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: THIS EVENT OCCURRED AT THE RAIL CAR UNLOAD/LOADING DOCK. TWO RAIL CARS WERE IN POSITION AT THE DOCK, ONE AT THE NORTH RACK AND ONE AT THE SOUTH RACK. SPENT ACID FROM BOTH CARS HAD BEEN OFF LOADED BY 4:22 AM. AFTER RETURNING FROM “LUNCH” THE OPERATOR BEGAN PREPARATION TO LOAD FRESH ACID INTO THE CAR AT THE SOUTH RACK. THE OPERATOR OPENED THE GATE VALVE ON THE ACID LINE TO THE CAR AT THE SOUTH RACK, SET HIS BATCH METER FOR 12,750 GALLONS, STARTED THE SOUTH ACID PUMP, AND AT 5:12 STARTED LOADING THE CAR WITH 99% ACID AT THE SOUTH RACK. HE THEN DID THE SAME THING AT THE NORTH RACK, SET HIS BATCH METER AND STARTED THE NORTH ACID PUMP TO FILL THE CAR. THE CAR AT THE SOUTH RACK, SHPX206777, HAS A LISTED STORAGE CAPACITY OF 13,140 GALLONS. AT 5:42:57 AM FRESH ACID STARTED TO OVERFLOW FROM THE CAR AT THE SOUTH RACK. THE OPERATOR REACTED AND BY 5:43:23 AM HAD SHUT DOWN THE FILLING OPERATION BY HITTING THE EMERGENCY STOP AT THE SOUTH RACK. THIS SHUT DOWN THE SOUTH PUMP AND CLOSED THE AIR OPERATED VALVE IN THE ACID LINE FEEDING THE SOUTH RACK. AFTER STOPPING THE ACID OVERFLOW AT THE SOUTH RACK THE OPERATOR WENT TO INSPECT THE CAR AT THE NORTH RACK. HE FOUND THAT HE HAD FAILED TO OPEN THE MANUAL GATE VALVE ON THE ACID FEED LINE TO THE TANK CAR SO NO ACID HAD ENTERED THE CAR. HE THEN WENT BACK AND SHUT DOWN THE NORTH ACID FEED PUMP AND AIR OPERATED VALVE. THE OPERATOR THEN WENT TO GET A PALLET OF SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED ACID. THE MAJORITY OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AT THE RAIL DOCK. AFTER DAYLIGHT, A SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID(10-15 GALLONS) WAS OBSERVED THROUGH THE CHAIN LINK FENCE ON BP’S PROPERTY WHICH WE ATTEMPTED TO NEUTRALIZE WITH SODA ASH.     REVIEW OF THE TAPE FROM THE RAIL DOCK CAMERA(S) WAS COMPLETED BY 9:00 AM. IT WAS THEN DETERMINED BASED ON THE TIME OF ACTUAL DISCHARGE AND APPROXIMATE FLOW THAT WE HAD EXCEEDED THE RQ FOR SULFURIC ACID. THE NRC WAS CONTACTED AT 9:08 AM FOLLOWED BY THE SERC AND LEPC. BP WAS CONTACTED AT THE SAME TIME AND INFORMED THAT A MINOR AMOUNT OF ACID WAS ON THEIR PROPERTY. THEY WERE ADVISED TO HAVE THEIR CONTRACTOR CLEAN UP THE SMALL SPILL AND BILL US FOR THE EXPENSE. EQ INDUSTRIAL SERVICES WAS CALLED IN FOR CLEAN UP SERVICES. A VAC TRUCK WAS USED TO COLLECT ACID FROM THE RAIL DOCK SUMP AS WELL AS FROM AREAS THAT COULD BE REACHED THROUGH THE FENCE ON THE BP SITE. CONTAMINATED SOIL WITH SODA ASH WAS REMOVED FROM A 150 FT. AREA AT THE RAIL DOCK. ALL LIQUID, STONE AND SOIL THAT WAS REMOVED FROM THE RAIL DOCK WAS PLACED IN THE DECONTAMINATION PIT FOR FURTHER WASHING AND NEUTRALIZATION. ALL WASTEWATER FROM THE DECONTAMINATION PIT DISCHARGES TO THE BP WASTE WATER TREATMENT SYSTEM. EQ WAS FINISHED WITH CLEANUP OPERATIONS BY 3:00 PM.     BY FAILING TO OPEN THE VALVE TO THE RAILCAR AT THE NORTH RACK, THE OPERATOR WAS USING TWO PUMPS TO FILL THE RAILCAR AT THE SOUTH RACK. THESE PUMP DISCHARGES SHARE A COMMON 6” LINE UP TO THE RAIL DOCK WHERE IT SPLITS INTO TWO SEPARATE FEED LINES, ONE TO THE NORTH RACK, ONE TO THE SOUTH RICK. IT
column169: THE EMPLOYEE HAS GONE THROUGH 2 DAYS OF RETRAINING ON RAILCAR ACID LOADING PROCEDURES. EMERGENCY HIGH LEVEL PUMP CUT-OFF PROBES WILL BE INSTALLED AT THE NORTH AND SOUTH LOADING RACKS TO PREVENT THE POSSIBILITY OF OVERFILLING RAILCARS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THE OCEAN CONTAINER VESSEL HORIZON TACOMA 670N WAS IN THE PACIFIC OCEAN EN ROUTE FROM TACOMA, WASHINGTON TO ANCHORAGE, ALASKA WHEN ROUGH WEATHER DAMAMGED SEVERAL CONTAINERS AND ROUGH WAVES KNOCKED THREE HAZARDOUS CONTAINER SHIPMENTS INTO THE SEA. THERE WERE NO LEAKS BUT THE LOSS OF THE COMPLETE OCEAN CONTAINER REQUIRED THE FILING OF SEVERAL REPORTS TO CAPTURE EACH HAZMAT SHIPMENT LOSS. THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED ALONG WITH AND EMPLOYEE FROM THE WAHSINGTON DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY. THE NOTIFICATION WAS LAOS MADE TO THE USCG LT.  THE CONTAINERS WERE NOT DISCOVERED MISSING UNTIL 12/19/2006 WHEN THE MATE COULD GO ON DECK ON SURVEY THE DAMAGE CAUSED BY TWO DAYS OF ROUGH WEATHER. THE SHIPPERS WERE NALCO, SPAN ALASKA TRANSPORTATION AND PACIFIC ALASKA FORWARDERS, SHIPPING UNDER BOOKING AND CONTAINER N.O.S. TX2016859/SEAU172414, WEB252642/SEAU872334 AND WEB102307/SEAU172102 RESPECTIVELY. A REPORT WILL BE FILED FOR EACH CHEMICAL THAT WAS LOST AT SEA.
column169: ALL SHIPMENTS WERE SECURED WELL BUT THE FORCE OF THE WAVES CAUSED THE STEEL CABLES AND PINS TO BREAK.

DURING SWITCHING IN THE RAILYIRD, TCIX 21143 WAS REPORTED EMANATING A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD WHEN THE SWITCH JOINT WAS MADE WITH OTHER RAILCARS. TCIX 21143 WAS CORNERED OFF AND SWITCHING ACTIVITIES CEASED. BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS INPECTED TCIX 21143 FINDING 2 OF 3 FLANGE BOLT NUTS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE T-CONNECTION TO THE VAPOR VALVE LOOSE. THIS T-CONNECTION IS SEATED ATOP A THICK RUBBER GASKET ABOVE THE PIPE FLANGE. THE 165 PSI PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE IS ALSO BOLTED ATOP THIS T-CONNECTION. RESPONDERS FOUND NO CORROSION ON THE BOLTS AND NUTS; AND TOOL TIGHTENED THE NUTS AFTER LOCK WASHERS WERE APPLIED. NO PRODUCT IMPACTED THE GROUND. AFTERWARDS, RESPONDERS NEUTRALIZED SPILLAGE WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WATER WASHED THE TOP OF TCIX 21143. RESPONSE WAS CONCLUDED BY 1530 HRS. CST, 12/22/06.

AFTERWARDS, TILX 400745 WAS RETURNED TO THE ORIGIN SHIPMENT LOCATION FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND PRODUCT DISTRIBUTION, AS THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE REJECTED THIS SHIPMENT.

A BNSF INTERMCDAL STACK TRAIN TRAVELING WEST ON BNSF MAIN TRACK 1 DERAILED THE LEAD TWO LOCOMOTIVES AND THE FOLLOWING 12 ARTICULATED INTERMODAL FLATCART TRANSPORTING 120 INTERMODAL CONTAINERS. THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS DERAILMENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER INVESTIGATION. THE INTERMODAL FLATCARS AND THE CONTAINERS RIDING ATOP THESE FLATCARS DERAILED IN A PILE. ONE CONTAINER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DESTINED FOR EXPORT, PONU 44224, CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE IN THE DERAILMENT PILE. 14 OF 30 STEEL DRUMS OF TOLUENE SOLUTION INSIDE THIS CONTAINER WERE DAMAGED AND COMPROMISED AS REPORTED BY THE BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS AT THE INCIDENT SITE. ALL DRUMS INSIDE THIS CONTAINER SUSTAINED VARIOUS DEGREES OF DAMAGE TO THE DRUM STRUCTURE AND THE COMPROMISED DRUMS WERE EITHER CRUSHED, SPLIT OR HAD THEIR DRUMS LIDS DISLODGED. THE NON-LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVER-PACKS AND STAGED FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL OR INCINERATION. AFTER ALL CONTENTS IN PONU 44224 WERE REMOVED, THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED AND STAGED FOR SCRAPPING. THE COMPROMISED DRUMS WERE DRAINED, CLEANED AND ALSO STAGED FOR SCRAPPING. IMPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS FOR INCINERATION AT AN APPROVED LOCATION.

column168: A BNSF OUTBOUND TRAIN CREW PICKING UP RAILCARS IN THE RAILYARD, DERAILED FIVE RAILCARS AT THE MAINLINE CROSSOVER SWITCH AT THE WEST YARD LEAD TRACK. THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT DURING THIS SHOVING MOVEMENT WAS THE FAILURE OF AN EMPLOYEE AT THE LEAD END OF THE MOVEMENT TO CONTROL THE MOVEMENT WHEN A SWITCH NOT LINED PROPERLY WAS ENCOUNTERED. TWO OF THE FIVE RAILCARS DERAILED ON THEIR SIDES AND THESE TWO WERE TANK CAR LOADS OF ALCOHOL. GATX 203717 ON ITS SIDE WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT AT THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE CONNECTION. A BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IMMEDIATELY APPLIED A "PLUG AND DIKE" SEALANT AROUND THE FLANGE AREA THAT STOPPED THE DRIPS. GATX 203717 WAS UPRIGHTED WHICH ENDED ANY FURTHER THREATENED PRODUCT RELEASE. ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED. THE PRODUCT IN GATX 203717 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR ON 1/08/07 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.

column14: EAST SMITH ROAD AT CHAMBERS RO
column168: Flying J Transportation driver was eastbound on Smith Road making a left turn to go northbound onto Chambers Road, Aurora, Colorado. The back rear passenger side tire on the tire collided with the median curb and the load shifted. The driver lost control of the transportation unit and rolled it onto its passenger side, colliding with a railroad crossing device. The collision resulted in the tearing of the tanker, causing approximately 4450 gallons of diesel fuel to escape onto the road surface and adjacent Union Pacific Railroad property.     The Aurora Police, Fire and HAZMAT departments responded to the scene. Fire and HAZMAT immediately placed absorbents and diking devices around the vehicle. Fuel entered the storm drain and contaminated the adjacent property. Flying J immediately notified their corporate response contractor and a crew immediately responded to the location. Remaining fuel in the tanker was removed, and major site remediation efforts began. Storm drain was cleaned of fuel and excavation efforts began on the contaminated soil surfaces.     Remediation efforts are continuing at the site.
column169: Transportation drivers will be refreshed on turning distances required to clear all obstacles while making turns with their vehicles.  This includes, but is not limited to: speed, clearances, obstacles with the turn path and other such factors.

column168: CRUSHED CARTON ALONG SIDE WITH POSSIBLE FORKLIFT PUNCTURE

A BNSF audit of hazardous material incidents revealed an incident that occurred on 12/14/06 in Clovis, NM that was inadvertently not previously reported:  An inbound BNSF intermodal train inspection in the railyard revealed container OOLU 576397 riding atop an entrained rail flatcar was leaking an unknown substance. This intermodal flatcar was set-out of the train for interior inspection of OOLU 576397. A BNSF contractor inspected OOLU 576397 and found two 55 gallon steel drums partially crushed by heavy lading (a 4500 lb. piece of equipment on a skid) that was stacked atop these drums with no layer separation. Poor blocking and bracing inside OOLU 576397 prevented a load shift that caused this heavy item atop the drums to move and the shifted weight partially crushed the sidewalls of the two drums below. The sidewall crushing resulted in small cracks in the sidewall and product leakage. The two leaking drums were placed into over-packs and returned inside OOLU 56397 after the spillage inside this container was wiped. This shipment was destined for export to Asia.
column169: Ensure shipper employs acceptable blocking and bracing techniques that would eliminate normal intransit load shifts. Also, provide layer separation platforms when lading is stacked atop other lading.

column168: Hitchcock Bros driver loaded a tractor trailer load of #2 home heating oil, then left Exxon Mobil in New Haven, CT. A few minutes after loading, the driver was making a right turn onto an on-ramp, when a Dodge Neon cut in front of the truck’s path to get in front of the truck. The truck driver needed to make an evasive maneuver to avoid the car, and as a result, the truck tipped onto it’s side, causing a spill of home heating oil. All spilled material was cleaned and removed within 7 hours, and no waterways were contaminated.
column169: It is our belief that the driver did his best to avoid the car that cut in front of the truck. The driver had just finished loading prior to the incident, and had driven this route for a number of years without prior incident. It was suggested that if possible, the driver should anticipate reckless operation of other vehicles whenever at or near intersections.

column168: EDWARDS OIL DRIVER WAS LOADING FUEL OIL FROM HIS CARGO TANKER TO AN ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK ON THE PROPERTY OF KEEWATIN TACONITE, THE DRIVER MIS-READ THE TANK CHART FOR THE STORAGE TANK.  CONSEQUENTLY, HE THOUGHT THE TANK COULD HOLD MORE FUEL THAN IT ACTUALLY COULD, WHEN HE BEGAN FILLING THE STORAGE TANK, THE TANK BECAME FULL AND EXCESS FUEL WAS SPILLED OUT OVER THE TOP OF THE STORAGE TANK INTO A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL, WHICH WAS THEN DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.
column169: SINCE THIS SPILL WAS PRIMARILY DUE TO DRIVER ERROR, WE RECOMMEND ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR THE DRIVER IN HOW TO CORRECTLY READ A TANK CHART, HOW TO ALLOW A 10% MARGIN IN CALCULATING THE TOTAL CAPACITY OF THE TANK, AND HOW TO BE IN A POSITION TO IMMEDIATELY STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT IN CASE THE TANK BECOMES FULL AND STARTS TO OVERFLOW.

column168: Mastermark, a supplier of printing ink, delivered a 4 oz plastic bottle of ink to The Boeing Company's internal mail distribution centing in Seattle, WA.  The bottle was packaged inside a fiberboard box, not properly marked, but did have two (2) Class 3 flammable liquid labels on the outside of each end of the box.  Mastermark included a MSDS and a partially filled out bill of lading indicating that the intended Boeing recipient was located in Jacksonville Florida.  The bill of lading was not properly filled out for the shipment of a hazardous material.    Somtime during the Boeing Christmas shutdown (Dec 22, 2007 to Jan 2, 2008) this item was placed in a fiberboard box that contained bulk mail and routed to the Boeing St. Louis facility via the internal mail distribution system.  Upon receipt, mailroom personnel in St. Louis alerted the facilities DOT/Hazardous material personnel.     There was no leakage or release of the printing ink during transit.
column169: The mailroom personnel in St. Louis notified DOT/Hazardous Material personnel who prepared appropriate paperwork, labeling, and markings for the item to be shipped from St. Louis to Jacksonville, Florida.

column168: A van containing hazardous materials overturned to excessive speed (25 MPH) while maing the transition from northbound I-405 Freeway to the southbound I-110 Freeway.  L.A. County Fire Department and Custom Chemical were notified and promptly responded. LA County Fire closed off the area and created barrier to prevent entry of the estimated 50-200 gallon of material which leaked from the van. Additional agencies were including the LA Country Health Department and Cal-Trans. Custom Chemical arranged for an emergency response company to contain, collect and cleanup the spilled materials. The storm sewer nearest the spill event was also cleaned by Custom Chemical emergency response contractors.
column169: The drivers were reinstructed that all speed warnings must be obeyed at all times.Loading personnel were instructed to load materials securely onto trucks and secure with appropriate load-locks or other security devices.

column168: While in transit from Lilly del Caribe, Inc. facility in Carolina PR (PR02/05) to Lilly del Caribe, Inc. facility in Mayaguez, PR(PR04) one of sixteen 5-gallon plastic drums developed a small leak.  The substance involved was   WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.(ACETONITRILE,ACETONE),3,UN1993,PGIII  The amount reported spilled was approximately 10 pounds(1.25 gallons).  The leak is believed to have developed due to a nail head that protruded from one of the wooden palettes used to hold the 5-gallon plastic drums.  Although, the drums were fastened together and to the palette via platic sheen-wrap; there was apparently enough abrasion caused by vibration in transit so that the nail head eroded a small section of the side of the bottom rim of one of the drums causing a small leak.    The leak was discovered by the driver and plant personnel at the Mayaguez facility during unloading.    The carrier was:  Valentin Trucking Services, Inc.  PO Box 7258 Pueblo Station  Carolina, PR 00986  USDOT: 974114  HazMat Registration No.: 092302 001 022K
column169: Although Lilly del Caribe, Inc. takes great care to inspect shipments of hazardous waste prior to transferring them to other sites, special care is now being taken to ensure that wooden palettes are in satisfactory condition with no loose or exposed nails or damaged wooden slats that could potentially damage plastic drums.  In addition, extra care will be taken to ensure immobility of the drums against to transit vibration in relation to the palette via tighter wrapping of the plastic sheen-wrap around the drums and palettes.

The box was found leaking what we believed to be blood. A 50/50 solution of bleach and water was applied to the spill and recovered in a salvage drum. The shipper was notified and subsequently advised that she had placed a 2.5 kg block of dry ice in the box. The contents of the box contained four human leqs (shin through the foot) used in medical research. The recipient was advised and offered to recover the shipment from FedEx. The recipient agreed that this was the wrong way to offer the freight and that they use specialized carriers to move this type of contents. We advised both the shipper & recipient that FedEx prohibits unprocessed human tissue. Because of the nature of the contents, FedEx chose not to open the package further than necessary. Additionally, due to amount of time that had elapsed, the FAA released the shipment to the recipient.
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: The box was found leaking in a ULD that had been loaded on FedEx aircraft N2O6FE. The ULD was removed from the aircraft, and the package was segregated. The spilled material was recovered. We obtained an MSDS from the shipper that clearly identified the material shipped as a regulated hazardous material. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection.

On 12/15/2006, CSXT Hazardous Materials was notified that PLMX 135248, load Anhydrous Ammonia, was derailed in Marriottsville, Md. PLMX 135248 derailed and rolled onto it's cars top with the protective housing buried in the Soft earth. During re-railing operations, a decision was made by the Incident Commander (Sykesville Assistant Fire Chief) that a one (1) mile voluntary precautionary evacuation be implemented. The voluntary evacuation lasted for approximately 2.5 hours while the car was rerailed. PLMX 135248 was rerailed without incident. 75 people voluntary evacuated to the Sykesville Fire Department during the rerailing operation. column168: UPRR’S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A DERAILMENT WITH RELEASE IN THE 18TH STREET YARD, KANSAS CITY, KS. WHILE BEING SWITCHED, UTLX 46776 DERAILED INTO A STANDING CUT OF CARS AND RELEASED PRODUCT FROM A DAMAGED AIR VALVE AND BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND DISPLACED MANWAY COVER. MR. SEKAVEC PLUGGED THE AIR VALVE WITH A WOODEN PLUG, TIGHTENED THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS AND CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO STOP THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.     HAZ-MAT RESPONSE (CONTRACTOR) RESPONDED VACUUMED RELEASED PRODUCT AND MELTED SNOW, WHICH WILL BE DISPOSED OF AFTER ANALYSIS. AFTER DISCUSSION WITH PAUL BELT, KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT, THE AREA WAS SCARIFIED AND TURNED TO AID IN EVAPORATION OF ANY REMAINING RELEASED MATERIAL.     NO OTHER REMEDIATION WAS PLANNED FOR THIS AREA. UTLX 46776 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK TRUCKS FOR TRANSPORTATION TO MAGELLAN PIPE LINE IN KANSAS CITY, KS, FOR USE.

The General Car Foreman at CSX Transportation’s rail yard in Birmingham, AL advised that an ACFX 71778, load Flammable Liquids, NOS (Crude Sulfate Turpentine) was reported to have an odor and was possibly leaking. The car foreman inspected the car and found a small amount of liquid product on top of the car. He reported that 1 of the manway securement bolts was less than hand tight and 4 other securement bolts were less than wrench tight. He made all the manway bolts wrench tight and the odor stopped. The car was released. The shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (report # 12182006024). The shipper was advised of the conditiom found on the car and the actions taken to correct them. column168: WE FOUND THE SPILL IN TRAILER 2500943, WHICH ORIGINATED IN OUR OAKLAND FACILITY. WE FOUND A PUDDLE 4-5 FEET ACROSS CENTERED AROUND 2 DRUMS. WHEN WE MOVED THE DRUMS A SMALL STREAM OF LIQUID CAME OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THEM. WE LAID THE DRUM OVER ON ITS SIDE TO STOP THE FLOW. THE FLUID WAS COMING OUT OF A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. I CALLED CHEMTREC FOR INSTRUCTIONS. WE PUT DOWN ABSORBENT, SWEPT IT UP, AND SET IT IN A PLASTIC BUCKET. WE HELD THE DRUM AND PAIL ASIDE.
column169: I BELIEVE THE PUNCTURE OCCURRED WHILE THE DRUMS WERE BEING HANDLED ON THE OAKLAND DOCK. THE HOLE IS SO SMALL THAT IT ONLY LEAKED WHEN WE MOVED THE DRUM, SO THE LOADER MAY NOT HAVE NOTICED. PERHAPS THE SHIPPER COULD PUT THE DRUMS ON GOOD-QUALITY PALLETS IN THE FUTURE?

column168: A FORKLIFT DRIVER (EMPLOYED BY TCI PRECISION, BY THE NAME OF MIKE M) SCRAPED THE SIDE OF THE DRUM WITH THE FORKLIFT LEAVING A SMALL HOLE ABOUT 1 1/2 FEET FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.

column168: ON 12/28/06 AT 19:13 HRS., A CALL WAS RECEIVED FROM CSX PSCC, WITH TRAINMASTER ONLINE. CSXT CREW Y20128 WAS SWITCHING IN THE YARD, WHEN THEY SMELLED AMMONIA IN THE AREA. SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL CALLED TO INSPECT SUSPECT CARS. ER PERSONNEL FOUND AMMONIA ODOR NEXT TO CAR JJJX 1019. INSPECTION FOUND THE THREADED CAP ON THE LIQUID LINE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT, AND VALVE HANDLE SLIGHTLY OPEN, ALLOWING VAPOR TO ESCAPE. THE VALVE WAS SECURED AND THREADED CLOSURE TIGHTENED. VAPOR PRESSURE ON CAR STABILIZED AT 81 PSI. RAIL CAR FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. CHEMTREC REPORT #12292006003 TO COVER INCIDENT. column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER PROCEEDING ON STATELINE ROAD INTO A SERIES OF GRADUAL CURVES TRAVELING AT   APPROXIMATELY 35-40 MPH. DRIVER REPORTS FEELING HIS RIGHT FRONT TRACTOR STEER TIRE LEAVE THE PAVEMENT; THAT HE AT FIRST ATTEMPTED TO "RIDE" THE PUSH TO THE RIGHT AS UNIT WAS LEAVING THE ROADWAY PAVEMENT INTO THE GRASSY DOWNWARD SLOPED BERM AND THAT HE THEN ATTEMPTED TO STEER BACK ONTO ROADWAY AND FELT THE TRAILER "PUSHING" HIM FIRST FROM THE RIGHT AND THEN TO THE LEFT (APPARENTLY AS THE UNIT ROLLED OVER). TWO EVERGREEN TYPE TREES, APPROX 30’ TALL, WERE STRUCK BY THE TRANSPORT UNIT AND ACTED AS A "STOPPING FORCE" TO SLOW DOWN AND STOP THE FORWARD PROGRESSION OF THE UNIT. THE TRANSPORT UNIT CAME TO REST, ABREAST OF THE NOTED TREES, WITH BOTH THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER (TRANSPORT UNIT) LYING ON THEIR RESPECTIVE DRIVERS SIDES. DRIVER WAS ASSISTED FROM THE DAMAGED TRACTOR BY HELP OF A RESIDENT FROM ACROSS THE STREET FROM WHERE THE TRANSPORT UNIT LEFT THE ROADWAY. APPROPRIATE CALLS WERE PLACED FROM THE SCENE TO 911 EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND COMPANY PERSONNEL CONTACT. COMPANY PERSONNEL RESPONDED WITH CALL/REPORTS TO THE INDIANA EPA (INCIDENT #2006-12-137), THE DEARBORN COUNTY LEPC, DEARBORN COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTACTED AND HAD THE GREATER CINCINNATI HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, INC. UNIT RESPOND.     AS TRANSPORT WAS LOADED AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT THE SITE WAS SPRAYED WITH FOAM MATERIAL AS PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE AND TO CONTROL ANY POTENTIAL SITUATIONS ASSOCIATED TO THE GASOLINE PRODUCT THAT WAS LOADED ON THE TRANSPORT. IT WAS FOUND THAT A HOUSING FOR THE PRODUCT LEVEL SENSOR OF COMPARTMENT NUMBER 2 OF THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING/SEEPING GASOLINE FROM THE INTERNAL GASKET AREA WHERE THE HOUSING MEETS THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. FROM THE IMPACT THAT THE TRANSPORT UNIT SUSTAINED IN THE ROLLOVER IT WAS, TO OUR IMPRESSION, QUITE AMAZING THAT THE ONLY FORM OF LEAKAGE FROM THE VESSEL WAS OF THIS NATURE. THE ACTUAL ALUMINUM TANK TRAILER VESSEL PORTION, MAN WAYS, ETC. ALL MAINTAINED THEIR INTEGRITY; WITH AS NOTED ABOVE THE SOURCE OF A SEEPAGE OF PRODUCT COMING FROM THE NOTED MECHANISM.    RESPONDERS PLACED SOP PADS BENEATH THIS AREA TO ASSIST IN ABSORPTION OF THE GASOLINE AS IT VACATED THE TRAILER UNIT, (IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DETERMINED THAT APPROX. 15 GALLONS OF GASOLINE LEAKED/SEEPED OUT OF THIS APPARATUS). AFTER THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS SECURED THE AREA, COMPANY PERSONNEL DRILLED HOLES INTO THE FOUR TRAILER COMPARTMENTS GOING THROUGH THE ACTUAL PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRAILER THAT WAS POINTING TOWARD THE SKY AS A RESULT OF THE ROLLOVER. RECLAIMED PRODUCT WAS THEN PUMPED OUT OF THE WRECKED TRAILER ONTO A SECOND TRAILER THAT WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE BY THE COMPANY. A PTO (POWER TAKE OFF) PUMP ON THE SECOND TRANSPORT TRACTOR WAS USED TO PUMP OUT THE PRODUCT FROM THE WRECKED TRAILER. AN ALUMINUM PUMP OUT TUBE WAS CONNECTED FROM THE SECOND (PUMPING TRANSPORT) INTO THE PREVIOUSLY MENTIONED HOLES THAT WERE DRILLED INTO THE SIDE OF THE OVERTURNED TRAILE
column169: OF NOTE PREVIOUSLY IN THIS REPORT; WE WERE IMPRESSED WITH THE OVERALL INTEGRITY OF THE HEIL TRAILER AND THE COMPONENT STRUCTURE IN REGARDS TO THIS ROLLOVER ACCIDENT. WE FEEL FORTUNATE THAT THE ROLLOVER AND IMPACT OF THE VEHICLE WHILE DOING SO RESULTED IN ONLY A SMALL SEEPAGE OF PRODUCT FROM A GASKET AREA FOR THE MOUNTING OF THE SENSOR BODY. THE "PACKAGING" IN THIS CASE WAS SUFFICIENT TO ALLOW THE MINIMAL EXPOSURE TO PRODUCT SPILLAGE AND LOSS.     FROM AN OPERATIONAL AND ENTWINED SAFETY PERSPECTIVE WE DO HOLD QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS AND REVIEW A VARIETY OF DRIVING AND ROADWAY CONCERNS WITH OUR WORK FORCE. ALL DRIVER PERSONNEL ARE INSTRUCTED IN PROPER LOADING, UNLOADING, DRIVING AND ASSOCIATED ACTIVITIES. DRIVERS ARE RE-TRAINED IN ANY PARTICULAR AREA WHEN ENGAGED IN AN INCIDENT THAT WARRANTS THAT APPROPRIATE RESPONSE.     THIS PARTICULAR ACCIDENT OCCURRED IN A SLOPPING GRADUAL CURVE TO THE LEFT ON A TWO LANE COUNTY ROADWAY. THE NATURAL INCLINATION IS FOR THE DRIVER, IN ORDER TO MAINTAIN HIS UNIT IN THE PROPER LANE, WOULD HUG THE SHOULDER A BIT TO MAINTAIN THE TRAILER IN THE LANE OF TRAVEL. IN THIS INCIDENT THE DRIVER PLACED HIS VEHICLE TOO CLOSE TO THE SHOULDER OF THE PAVEMENT AND RESULTED WITH THE TRUCK EXITING THE ROADWAY. THESE TYPES OF RURAL ROADWAYS ARE VERY COMMON AND IT IS A CONTINUING EFFORT TO ADVISE OUR DRIVERS TO MAINTAIN PROPER POSITIONING OF THEIR UNITS AT ALL TIME. THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT AND WILL BE SUBJECT OF DISCUSSION IN OUR NEXT QUARTERLY DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS DURING THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2007 TO REINFORCE THE POTENTIAL IMPACTS OF THIS TYPE OF ACCIDENT AND HOW TO WORK TOWARD AVOIDANCE OF SAME.     FROM A REGULATORY STANDPOINT THE SITUATION WAS RESOLVED IN A POSITIVE MANNER. EMPLOYEE WITH THE INDIANA EPA WHO RESPONDED TO THE SITE, COMMENTED THAT HE WAS IMPRESSED WITH OUR COMPANY’S PROFESSIONAL AND TIMELY RESPONSE TO MITIGATING THE INCIDENT.     AS PREPARED AND SUBMITTED, THIS DATE OF JANUARY 8, 2007

column168: UPRR s Response Management Communications Center notified Manager Chemical Transportation Safety of a tank car reported to be releasing product in the Mason City, IA, yard at the north end of track 3. Manager Chemical Transportation Safety spoke with the Footboard Yardmaster in Mason City who advised the car released product only on movement. Manager Chemical Transportation Safety made contact with Midwest Grain Producers in Lakota, IA, and requested that MGP send personnel to inspect and secure the tank car. Midwest Grain Producers in Lakota advised  Manager Chemical Transportation Safety that, upon inspection, it was determined the valve stern on the pressure relief valve was broken and unable to be secured. Midwest Grain Producers in Lakota stated RESCAR (Repair Contractor) was responding to install a replacement valve to allow the car to continue in transportation. Following installation of the replacement valve, a one-time movement authority was obtained on behalf of MGP to allow the car to continue to destination for unloading and then return to Lakota for requalification. No remediation was required as the released material had been confined to the tank car with minimal amounts reaching the right-of-way.

column168: NCSC Team Leader Hazmat, notified Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, that ACFX 72546 was reported to be placarded but did not have proper shipping descriptions on the crew's paperwork. Investigation by NCSC Team Leader Hazmat indicated the car had been rinsed by the shipper (Romic Environmental) but had not been cleaned and purged. Paperwork provided by MHF Logistics indicated the car had been cleaned. Conversations with Romic, indicated the car was being filled when a defective bottom outlet valve was detected. The car was pumped out and stenciled Leaky tank, do not load. No FRA movement authority covering the defective valve was evident in any of the paperwork submitted by MHF Logistics. Romic advised the car was moving to Compass Environmental for DOT cleaning. Inspection of the tank car revealed a defective air valve on top of the car (unable to be closed) and the plug out of the air valve (reinstalled). One of the six manway swing bolts was unable to be secured as the nut was missing. Finally a rope was found leading into the manway opening and the manway cover was closed and secured. Opening the manway, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety found a pipe apparently used to pump out the tank car. The rope was placed into the car and the manway cover resecured. Manager Chemical Transportation Safety worked with Romic and MHF Logistics to obtain the proper paperwork to allow the car to continue in transportation.
column169: Insure shippers follow DOT regulations for moving tank cars.

AT 15:42 PM, THE MANAGER INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND THREE OF THE SIX MANWAY BOLTS TO BE LOOSE.  IT APPEARS THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE SECURED IN A CIRCULAR FASHION, STARTING AT THE #1 BOLT ADJACENT TO THE HINGE, AND WORKED IN A CLOCKWISE FASHION. THE MANWAY WAS THEN PROPERLY SECURED, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE TANKCAR, WHERE IT WAS LEFT TO HARDEN BY SHIPPER.
